			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It's not easy to design and balance a game.  It's even harder to patch it without breaking it.
<br />

<br />
The sorcerer is a solid class.  Its hard to think of new abilities that wont break the overall balance.
<br />

<br />
Give sorc insta AoE stun, for exemple, and you have many other class crying and demanding bolt mez.
<br />

<br />
So i was wondering, how to improve our survivability (a major concern) without increasing CC powers, and without increasing armor (cloth is cloth)?   
<br />

<br />
I watched the summoner classes, and it occured to me that, contrary to the sorc pet, they have pets that actually increase their survival in RvR.  Cabalist and 'chanters have pets that STUN, and the spiritmaster warrior can interrcept and block attacks.  
<br />
Sure, we can grab a cockatrice pet, and stun, but it's very circumstancial.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So... why not find a way to use the pet to increase sorcerer survivability...  
<br />

<br />
I came up with this idea...  I think it's on the verge of beeing too strong, the line between usefull and overpowered is so thin.  It would need testing, that's for sure...  Anyways, here goes, please comment:
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
New Spell Type:  Life links
<br />
Specialisation: mind
<br />
Effect: As you recieve damage, a % of that damage is redirected to the pet.
<br />

<br />
level 27 Minor Life link:      Pet absorbs 25% of damage dealt to sorcerer.
<br />
level 37 Life Link:              Pet absorbs 50% of damage dealt to sorcerer.
<br />
level 47 Life Link:              Pet absorbs 75% of damage dealt to sorcerer.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Basically, most sorc would have the 25% spell, giving them a kind off dmg reduction of 25% as long as they have a pet.   Most would have to decide if they want the 50% one (since it's 37 and many sorc use only 32-36 mind) for a cut in damage.  And only crazy high mind would get the powerfull 75%.   
<br />

<br />
What do you think?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
